00:14:23,360 --> 00:14:24,190
Yes.

249
00:14:26,160 --> 00:14:28,196
I have a 2-year-old. Ned.

250
00:14:32,120 --> 00:14:35,112
He's got blue eyes
and sort of sandy-colored hair...

251
00:14:35,200 --> 00:14:37,316
...and he's about 2'3".

252
00:14:38,880 --> 00:14:40,598
And his mum left.

253
00:14:41,120 --> 00:14:43,634
-Really?
-Yeah.

254
00:14:44,240 --> 00:14:47,437
Yeah, I mean,
obviously it was a very big shock...

255
00:14:47,720 --> 00:14:50,029
...because we were so happy, you know?

256
00:14:50,120 --> 00:14:53,556
Sandra's neurology practice
was just up and running...

257
00:14:54,200 --> 00:14:58,557
...and then one day her bags were packed,
and my best friend was waiting outside...

258
00:14:58,640 --> 00:15:00,039
...in his Ferrari.

259
00:15:00,120 --> 00:15:01,758
Yeah. You know, the Modena?

260
00:15:01,840 --> 00:15:06,709
The one with the supercharged engine,
where you can see it through the back window?

261
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:11,117
-You got dumped then?
-Yeah.

262
00:15:15,280 --> 00:15:17,919
SUZlE: May I ask, does your ex see Ned at all?

263
00:15:20,120 --> 00:15:22,270
Sorry, I didn't catch your name.

264
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:23,630
Suzie.

265
00:15:23,960 --> 00:15:25,109
Suzie.

266
00:15:25,680 --> 00:15:28,035
She doesn't see much of him, no.

267
00:15:28,400 --> 00:15:30,470
How does he cope with that?

268
00:15:30,720 --> 00:15:32,312
He's a very good little boy.

269
00:15:32,400 --> 00:15:34,550
Very, very brave.

270
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:36,870
They've got amazing resources, don't they?

271
00:15:36,960 --> 00:15:39,474
Just the other day I was thinking about my ex.

272
00:15:39,560 --> 00:15:43,951
He came crawling up, put his little pudgy arms
around my neck, and he said:

273
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:45,991
"You hang in there, Dad."

274
00:15:46,480 --> 00:15:48,789
God, that's amazing for a 2-year-old!

275
00:15:49,920 --> 00:15:51,069
Is it?

276
00:15:51,160 --> 00:15:52,957
[Affirmative sounds]

277
00:15:53,520 --> 00:15:56,318
Yeah, he's very special. Very, very special.

278
00:15:56,400 --> 00:15:59,233
Sometimes I think, you know,
he's the one taking care of me.

279
00:15:59,320 --> 00:16:01,754
Teaching me the ways of the world.

280
00:16:03,920 --> 00:16:05,194
Sorry.

281
00:16:09,280 --> 00:16:10,156
Thank you.

282
00:16:10,240 --> 00:16:13,232
WlLL: My God, what a performance!
I was even fooling myself.

283
00:16:13,320 --> 00:16:15,914
[Light, funky instrumental music]

284
00:16:18,760 --> 00:16:20,955
There you go. You okay?

285
00:16:21,040 --> 00:16:22,359
Yeah. Perfect, thanks.

286
00:16:22,440 --> 00:16:23,873
-Trust me?
-Of course.

287
00:16:23,960 --> 00:16:26,554
WlLL: By the end of the evening,
I had a date lined up.

288
00:16:26,640 --> 00:16:28,551
ALL: Single parents alone together!

289
00:16:28,640 --> 00:16:32,792
Single parents alone together!
All for one and one for all!

290
00:16:34,960 --> 00:16:38,873
WlLL: The problem was I also had
an imaginary 2-year-old son.

291
00:17:08,400 --> 00:17:12,313
The date was a SPAT picnic in Regent's Park,
with everyone bringing their kids.

292
00:17:12,840 --> 00:17:14,193
Sadly, Ned couldn't be there.

293
00:17:14,280 --> 00:17:16,840
His mum had come
and picked him up at the last second.

294
00:17:16,920 --> 00:17:18,478
-What a shame.
-Yeah.

295
00:17:18,560 --> 00:17:19,709
I'm sorry.

296
00:17:19,800 --> 00:17:22,997
-Got it.
-This is Megan, by the way.

297
00:17:23,240 --> 00:17:24,559
Hello, Megan.

298
00:17:24,640 --> 00:17:25,470
Yeah.

299
00:17:25,560 --> 00:17:27,869
A friend of mine from SPAT
isn't feeling so great...

300
00:17:27,960 --> 00:17:30,554
...so I said that we'd take her kid
to the picnic, too.

301
00:17:30,640 --> 00:17:32,676
-ls that all right?
-Yeah.

302
00:17:32,760 --> 00:17:35,069
The more the merrier. Right.

303
00:17:35,160 --> 00:17:36,878
Come on, slowcoach!

304
00:17:40,160 --> 00:17:41,639
MARCUS: I hated that SPAT lot.

305
00:17:41,720 --> 00:17:46,874
Mum's friend Suzie was fine, but now there
was that wally who wanted to get off with her.

306
00:17:46,960 --> 00:17:48,791
Marcus, Will. Will, Marcus.

307
00:17:49,200 --> 00:17:50,474
Hi there.

308
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:52,955
Right.

309
00:17:53,040 --> 00:17:57,875
Pile in, everyone.
Look what a mess Ned made of the car seat.

310
00:17:59,520 --> 00:18:01,272
What a shame he can't come.

311
00:18:01,680 --> 00:18:03,398
So, what do you do?

312
00:18:04,160 --> 00:18:05,036
Me?

313
00:18:06,240 --> 00:18:09,630
WlLL: There were too many lies
to keep track of so I told the truth.

314
00:18:09,720 --> 00:18:13,030
-Nothing.
-Well, before then.

315
00:18:13,680 --> 00:18:16,353
-What do you mean, before I did nothing?
-Yeah.

316
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:18,277
I did nothing.

317
00:18:18,880 --> 00:18:21,235
You've never worked?

318
00:18:21,400 --> 00:18:25,837
I've done the odd day here and there, but, no.

319
00:18:27,240 --> 00:18:28,753
Crazy, isn't it?

320
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:30,075
It's....

321
00:18:34,280 --> 00:18:35,269
Brilliant.

322
00:18:36,600 --> 00:18:39,194
WlLL: My God, I was going to have to tell her.

323
00:18:39,280 --> 00:18:43,876
What happened, in fact,
was that my dad wrote a song...

324
00:18:43,960 --> 00:18:47,714
...in 1958, and it's quite a famous song...

325
00:18:47,800 --> 00:18:51,031
...and I basically live off the royalties of that.

326
00:18:51,120 --> 00:18:52,439
You know Michael Jackson?

327
00:18:52,520 --> 00:18:54,317
He makes a $1,000,000 a minute.

328
00:18:54,400 --> 00:18:56,550
That's $60,000,000 an hour.

329
00:18:56,640 --> 00:18:58,358
I don't make a $1,000,000 a minute.

330
00:18:58,440 --> 00:19:00,192
-Nothing like, sadly.
-How much then?

331
00:19:00,280 --> 00:19:01,395
Marcus!

332
00:19:01,480 --> 00:19:05,268
WlLL: I was beginning to wonder
if we'd be stuck with this weird kid all day.

333
00:19:05,360 --> 00:19:07,396
So, what's this song then?

334
00:19:08,120 --> 00:19:11,078
If you can live off it, we must've heard of it.

335
00:19:11,400 --> 00:19:13,550
It's Santa's Super Sleigh.

336
00:19:13,640 --> 00:19:15,790
WlLL: God, please don't sing it.

337
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:21,199
[Sings] "Look who's coming round the bend
It's Santa and his reindeer friends

338
00:19:21,280 --> 00:19:25,910
"With a ho, ho, ho and a hey, hey, hey,
It's Santa's super sleigh"

339
00:19:26,840 --> 00:19:29,070
I expect people do that all the time.

340
00:19:29,560 --> 00:19:31,790
No, I think you two are the first.

341
00:19:31,880 --> 00:19:35,634
Sorry. I don't understand.
How does that make you money?

342
00:19:36,120 --> 00:19:38,076
Do carol singers have to pay you 10 percent?

343
00:19:38,160 --> 00:19:41,516
They should, but you can't
always catch the little bastards.

344
00:19:41,600 --> 00:19:44,637
So, how often do you look after him?
Marcus.

345
00:19:44,720 --> 00:19:46,756
Every once in a while.

346
00:19:47,520 --> 00:19:49,715
His mum's a little off-color sometimes.

347
00:19:49,800 --> 00:19:52,155
MARCUS: You call it off-color, I call it nuts.

348
00:19:52,280 --> 00:19:55,556
She's not nuts, Marcus.
She just needs a weekend taking it easy.

349
00:19:55,640 --> 00:19:59,349
We'll have a nice picnic, and when
you get home, she'll be all rested up.

350
00:19:59,440 --> 00:20:02,193
My God! What the hell is that?

351
00:20:02,280 --> 00:20:03,952
My mum's homemade bread.

352
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:07,876
It looks pretty good.

353
00:20:07,960 --> 00:20:09,996
No, it isn't. It's healthy.

354
00:20:11,240 --> 00:20:14,073
[Ducks quacking
light, cheerful instrumental music]

355
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:49,476
You miss him, don't you?

356
00:20:51,320 --> 00:20:52,150
Who?

357
00:20:54,400 --> 00:20:55,389
Ned!

358
00:20:56,160 --> 00:20:57,149
Yeah.

359
00:20:57,840 --> 00:20:59,956
Yeah, very much.

360
00:21:00,040 --> 00:21:01,712
He'd have loved this.

361
00:21:04,400 --> 00:21:06,231
I think I killed a duck.

362
00:21:09,720 --> 00:21:11,597
MARCUS: I was only trying to feed it.

363
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:14,629
WlLL: What's that floating
in the water next to it?

364
00:21:14,720 --> 00:21:16,597
Is thatyour mum's bread?

365
00:21:16,800 --> 00:21:20,156
You didn't have to throw the whole loaf.
That would've killed me.

366
00:21:20,840 --> 00:21:24,037
You the one who was throwing
bloody great loaves at the ducks?

367
00:21:24,200 --> 00:21:26,998
Yeah, he was, but I've stopped him now.

368
00:21:27,080 --> 00:21:29,389
You know, boys will be boys, and all that.

369
00:21:29,480 --> 00:21:30,435
So he killed it.

370
00:21:30,520 --> 00:21:33,478
No. Sorry, I misunderstood you.
The duck was dead already.

371
00:21:33,560 --> 00:21:36,233
He was throwing bread
to try and sink the body...

372
00:21:36,320 --> 00:21:38,709
...because Megan here was getting upset.

373
00:21:41,200 --> 00:21:44,192
Marcus wouldn't kill a duck.
Would you, Marcus?

374
00:21:44,280 --> 00:21:47,989
No. I love ducks. They're my
second favorite animal after dolphins.

375
00:21:48,080 --> 00:21:50,719
They can kill sharks with their noses.

376
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:55,309
I'll have to wade in and get it.

377
00:21:55,640 --> 00:21:58,632
Listen, I hope it's not some sort of epidemic.

378
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:02,833
I think we beat the rap there, mate.

379
00:22:03,520 --> 00:22:05,158
Yeah. Well.

380
00:22:07,760 --> 00:22:08,954
FlONA: Marcus?

381
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:15,309
Mum.

382
00:22:25,320 --> 00:22:29,472
MARCUS: That day, the Dead Duck Day,
was when it all began.

383
00:22:30,200 --> 00:22:34,273
That bloke Will just followed us in
and I didn't tell him not to.

384
00:22:34,440 --> 00:22:38,513
Afterwards, I realized that there was no way
I could have been nervous just then...

385
00:22:38,600 --> 00:22:42,388
...because just then I didn't know
there was anything to be nervous about.

386
00:22:42,480 --> 00:22:45,313
But then I put the key in the lock,
opened the door....

387
00:22:45,400 --> 00:22:46,549
SUZlE: Are you decent?

388
00:22:47,120 --> 00:22:49,509
MARCUS: And a new part of my life started.

389
00:22:49,600 --> 00:22:50,715
Bang!

390
00:22:50,800 --> 00:22:52,597
[Dramatic music]

391
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:56,194
[Baby crying]

392
00:22:56,280 --> 00:22:57,713
Jesus Christ.

393
00:22:57,880 --> 00:22:58,835
SUZlE: Oh, my God.

394
00:22:59,640 --> 00:23:02,598
-Will, call an ambulance.
-Marcus, where's the phone?

395
00:23:03,600 --> 00:23:05,750
Where's the phone, mate?

396
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:08,991
[Ambulance siren wails]

397
00:23:16,040 --> 00:23:18,634
[Soft, dramatic instrumental music]

398
00:23:21,760 --> 00:23:23,716
WlLL: It was horrible. Horrible.

399
00:23:24,400 --> 00:23:27,597
But driving fast behind the ambulance
was fantastic.

400
00:23:28,400 --> 00:23:29,389
SUZlE: She's conscious.

401
00:23:29,680 --> 00:23:31,557
She was okay in the ambulance.

402
00:23:31,640 --> 00:23:33,073
She was asking after you, Marcus.

403
00:23:33,160 --> 00:23:34,878
That's nice of her.

404
00:23:35,960 --> 00:23:39,589
Listen, you know this has
nothing to do with you, don't you?

405
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:42,720
I mean, you're not the reason that she....

406
00:23:43,040 --> 00:23:46,669
You're not the reason that she's here.
Isn't that right, Will?

407
00:23:49,080 --> 00:23:51,230
Yeah, that's right.

408
00:23:52,720 --> 00:23:54,438
I'll go get you some water.

409
00:23:54,640 --> 00:23:57,552
-I can get that.
-No, you're okay.

410
00:23:57,640 --> 00:23:59,631
[Phone rings in background]

411
00:24:04,960 --> 00:24:06,712
Your mum's going to be okay.

412
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:08,119
Yeah, I suppose.

413
00:24:08,720 --> 00:24:11,234
That's not the point, though, is it?

414
00:24:11,320 --> 00:24:14,278
Right, you mean you're afraid
she might try again?

415
00:24:14,360 --> 00:24:16,191
Just shut up, all right?

416
00:24:17,920 --> 00:24:19,956
There you go, warm and flat.

417
00:24:20,160 --> 00:24:21,593
Are you with Fiona Brewer?

418
00:24:21,680 --> 00:24:23,033
Yes, I'm her friend Suzie.

419
00:24:23,120 --> 00:24:25,793
This is Marcus and Will.

420
00:24:25,880 --> 00:24:28,440
She's recovering well,
but we'll keep her overnight.

421
00:24:28,520 --> 00:24:33,230
I'm going to get a consent form for Ms. Brewer
so the boy can stay with you two tonight.

422
00:24:33,480 --> 00:24:34,629
Right.

423
00:24:37,080 --> 00:24:39,150
So, my place or yours?

424
00:24:39,640 --> 00:24:40,755
Sorry.

425
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:44,271
[Soft, slow guitar music]

426
00:24:53,520 --> 00:24:54,555
Okay.

427
00:24:54,640 --> 00:24:57,200
-I should get back to Ned, I think.
-I'll take that.

428
00:24:57,280 --> 00:24:58,554
All right.

429
00:24:58,640 --> 00:25:00,631
WlLL: All in all, this was very interesting.

430
00:25:00,720 --> 00:25:02,756
So I'll call.

431
00:25:02,840 --> 00:25:05,229
WlLL: But I wouldn't want to do it every night.

432
00:25:05,320 --> 00:25:06,355
See you soon.

433
00:25:06,440 --> 00:25:09,398
WILL: The thing is,
a person's life is like a TV show.

434
00:25:09,520 --> 00:25:11,750
I was the star ofThe Will Show.

435
00:25:11,880 --> 00:25:14,917
And The Will Show wasn't an ensemble drama.

436
00:25:15,080 --> 00:25:17,514
Guests came and went, but I was the regular.

437
00:25:17,600 --> 00:25:19,909
It came down to me, and me alone.

438
00:25:20,320 --> 00:25:23,198
If Marcus' mum
couldn't manage her own show...

439
00:25:23,280 --> 00:25:27,159
...if her ratings were falling,
it was sad, but that was her problem.

440
00:25:27,320 --> 00:25:32,189
Ultimately, the whole single-mum plot line
was a bit complicated for me.

441
00:25:38,200 --> 00:25:40,395
[Sad, soft-rock folk song]

442
00:27:01,120 --> 00:27:03,953
I got the letter. Thanks.

443
00:27:06,880 --> 00:27:09,872
Oh, my God. I'd forgotten.

444
00:27:11,040 --> 00:27:12,359
You forgot?

445
00:27:12,440 --> 00:27:13,998
You forgot a suicide letter?

446
00:27:14,080 --> 00:27:17,390
I didn't think I'd have to remember it, did l?

447
00:27:21,440 --> 00:27:24,318
Did you read the part
where I said I'd always love you?

448
00:27:24,400 --> 00:27:27,358
It's a bit hard for you
to love me when you're dead, isn't it?

449
00:27:27,440 --> 00:27:28,759
I'm sorry.

450
00:27:35,800 --> 00:27:39,679
I can understand why you're angry, Marcus.

451
00:27:44,880 --> 00:27:48,111
I don't feel the same as I did yesterday,
if that's any help.

452
00:27:48,200 --> 00:27:49,110
What?

453
00:27:49,560 --> 00:27:51,312
It's all just gone away? All that?

454
00:27:51,800 --> 00:27:52,789
No, but...

455
00:27:54,080 --> 00:27:57,197
...at the moment, I feel better.

456
00:27:57,520 --> 00:27:59,351
"At the moment" is no good to me.

457
00:27:59,440 --> 00:28:02,989
I can see you feel better at the moment.
You just put the kettle on.

458
00:28:03,080 --> 00:28:06,993
But what happens when you finish your tea?
What happens when I go back to school?

459
00:28:07,080 --> 00:28:10,436
-I can't be here to watch you all the time.
-I know.

460
00:28:11,680 --> 00:28:15,389
We have to look after each other. The two of us.

461
00:28:16,280 --> 00:28:19,955
MARCUS: Suddenly I realized
two people isn't enough.

462
00:28:20,440 --> 00:28:21,634
You need a backup.

463
00:28:21,720 --> 00:28:24,837
If you're only two people,
and someone drops off the edge...

464
00:28:24,920 --> 00:28:26,433
...then you're on your own.

465
00:28:26,520 --> 00:28:28,158
Two isn't a large enough number.

466
00:28:28,240 --> 00:28:30,117
You need three, at least.

467
00:28:30,480 --> 00:28:33,040
-Three what?
-Nothing.

468
00:28:33,560 --> 00:28:35,232
MARCUS: But I'd had a great idea.

469
00:28:36,320 --> 00:28:39,756
WlLL: The important thing in island living
is to be your own activities director.

470
00:28:39,840 --> 00:28:42,479
I find the key is to think of a day
as units of time...

471
00:28:42,560 --> 00:28:45,836
...each unit consisting
of no more than 30 minutes.

472
00:28:45,920 --> 00:28:48,195
Full hours can be a little bit intimidating...

473
00:28:48,280 --> 00:28:50,635
...and most activities take about half an hour.

474
00:28:50,720 --> 00:28:52,392
Taking a bath: One unit.

475
00:28:52,960 --> 00:28:54,279
Watching Countdown:

476
00:28:54,360 --> 00:28:55,679
Okay....

477
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:57,035
WlLL: One unit.

478
00:28:57,960 --> 00:28:59,916
Web-based research:

479
00:29:01,520 --> 00:29:02,475
Two units.

480
00:29:02,560 --> 00:29:05,916
Exercising: Three units.

481
00:29:06,760 --> 00:29:09,433
Having my hair carefully disheveled: Four units.

482
00:29:09,520 --> 00:29:11,590
It's amazing how the day fills up.

483
00:29:11,680 --> 00:29:13,716
I often wonder, to be absolutely honest...

484
00:29:13,800 --> 00:29:16,360
...if I'd ever really have time for a job.

485
00:29:17,240 --> 00:29:19,196
How do people cram them in?

486
00:29:19,280 --> 00:29:21,077
[Cell phone rings]

487
00:29:24,360 --> 00:29:25,679
Yeah, Will here.

488
00:29:25,960 --> 00:29:27,996
MARCUS: It's Marcus.
WlLL: Pardon?

489
00:29:28,160 --> 00:29:29,354
It's Marcus.

490
00:29:29,440 --> 00:29:30,555
WlLL: Marcus?

491
00:29:31,200 --> 00:29:33,509
Marcus. Hi.

492
00:29:34,520 --> 00:29:36,272
How'd you get my number?

493
00:29:36,480 --> 00:29:37,390
From Suzie.

494
00:29:37,480 --> 00:29:40,278
I thought you'd like to take me out for the day
on Saturday.

495
00:29:40,360 --> 00:29:42,157
And why did you think that, Marcus?

496
00:29:42,240 --> 00:29:43,878
Suzie said we hit it off.

497
00:29:43,960 --> 00:29:45,678
WlLL: Did she?
MARCUS: Yeah.

498
00:29:45,800 --> 00:29:48,598
-And you said, "See you soon."
-I said what?

499
00:29:48,680 --> 00:29:49,669
MARCUS: "See you soon. "

500
00:29:49,760 --> 00:29:53,355
The night you dropped us off. Remember?
You said, "See you soon."

501
00:29:53,520 --> 00:29:57,308
This is soon, all right, Marcus.

502
00:29:57,560 --> 00:30:00,711
The thing is, mate,
my life is kind of hectic at the moment.

503
00:30:00,800 --> 00:30:02,791
Why? I thought you did nothing.

504
00:30:03,840 --> 00:30:07,628
I've got Ned and stuff to look after.

505
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:11,356
Matter of fact, I should be on the way
to preschool right now.

506
00:30:11,440 --> 00:30:12,634
What's that noise?

507
00:30:12,720 --> 00:30:14,199
That's a lawn mower.

508
00:30:14,280 --> 00:30:16,953
So, you know, just time-wise it's not....

509
00:30:18,480 --> 00:30:21,517
Tell you what, just hold the line one sec.

510
00:30:21,600 --> 00:30:23,352
Hold on, one sec. Thanks.

511
00:30:23,440 --> 00:30:25,396
WlLL: But then I thought, "Why not?"

512
00:30:25,480 --> 00:30:28,119
Why shouldn't I take
the poor little sod out for a meal?

513
00:30:28,200 --> 00:30:31,351
I could be Uncle Will.
Cool Uncle Will, King of the Kids.

514
00:30:32,920 --> 00:30:34,831
Okay, Marcus. You're on.

515
00:30:34,920 --> 00:30:36,831
I'll come if you take my mum, too.

516
00:30:36,920 --> 00:30:40,754
She has no money, so we'll have to go
somewhere cheap or you'll have to treat us.

517
00:30:40,840 --> 00:30:43,149
Listen, don't beat about the bush, Marcus.

518
00:30:43,240 --> 00:30:46,118
Why should l? We're poor.
You're rich. You pay.

519
00:30:46,200 --> 00:30:47,952
Bring your little boy, I don't mind.

520
00:30:48,040 --> 00:30:49,314
That's really big of you.

521
00:30:49,400 --> 00:30:51,436
Fine. Come round at 12:30 or something.

522
00:30:51,520 --> 00:30:52,714
Remember where we live?

523
00:30:52,800 --> 00:30:56,952
Flat 2, 31 Craysfield Road,
lslington, London, N12SF.

524
00:30:57,040 --> 00:30:58,553
England, the world, the universe.

525
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:01,154
MARCUS: Yeah.
WlLL: Marcus?

526
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:09,117
So, Fiona, how are you?

527
00:31:10,440 --> 00:31:14,831
-I mean, how are you feeling?
-My stomach's fine.

528
00:31:15,880 --> 00:31:17,029
Great.

529
00:31:18,320 --> 00:31:20,834
I must still be a bit barmy, though.

530
00:31:20,920 --> 00:31:23,912
This kind of thing doesn't go away overnight,
does it?

531
00:31:24,840 --> 00:31:25,829
No.

532
00:31:28,320 --> 00:31:32,279
MARCUS: If Mum was going to get Will to marry
her, she'd have to quit making jokes.

533
00:31:32,360 --> 00:31:33,429
At least she looked good.

534
00:31:33,520 --> 00:31:35,158
I had her put on that nice hairy jumper...

535
00:31:35,240 --> 00:31:38,152
...and the earrings she got from her friend
that went to Zimbabwe.

536
00:31:38,240 --> 00:31:40,435
WlLL: The kid seemed to think
this was a date.

537
00:31:40,520 --> 00:31:42,715
As for his mum, she was clearly insane...

538
00:31:42,800 --> 00:31:45,837
...and appeared to be wearing
some kind of Yeti costume.

539
00:31:45,920 --> 00:31:48,992
This had better be quick.
We were definitely not ordering starters.

540
00:31:49,080 --> 00:31:50,638
I'll start with the artichoke, please.

541
00:31:50,720 --> 00:31:53,712
Then I'll have a mushroom omelet with fries
and a Coke.

542
00:31:53,800 --> 00:31:56,678
-I'll have the vegetable platter.
-We're vegetarians.

543
00:31:56,960 --> 00:31:57,949
I'd never have guessed.

544
00:31:58,040 --> 00:32:00,315
Steak sandwich, please, mate. Thanks.

545
00:32:04,040 --> 00:32:05,917
MARCUS: This was going really well.

546
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:09,879
I wondered if we were going to move into
Will's place or move into someplace new.

547
00:32:11,960 --> 00:32:16,033
[Sings] "l heard he sang a good song

548
00:32:16,680 --> 00:32:19,558
"l heard he had a style"

549
00:32:21,160 --> 00:32:23,833
WlLL: I knew, of course,
the song couldn't last forever...

550
00:32:23,920 --> 00:32:26,388
...that I'd soon be at home, tucked up in bed.

551
00:32:26,480 --> 00:32:28,869
I knew it, but I couldn't feel it.

552
00:32:30,280 --> 00:32:33,431
[Sings] "And there he was, this young boy"

553
00:32:33,720 --> 00:32:36,792
WlLL: I must've been insane.
All I'd wanted was a date with Suzie.

554
00:32:36,880 --> 00:32:38,279
This was my punishment.

555
00:32:38,360 --> 00:32:42,478
[Sings] "Strumming my pain with his fingers"

556
00:32:43,960 --> 00:32:46,599
WlLL: The worst part was
when they closed their eyes.

557
00:32:46,800 --> 00:32:49,553
[Sings] "Killing me softly with his song

558
00:32:49,640 --> 00:32:51,392
"Killing me softly"

559
00:32:52,040 --> 00:32:53,678
Come sing with us, Will.

560
00:32:54,120 --> 00:32:56,588
I should really get going. Thanks.

561
00:32:58,160 --> 00:33:00,879
WlLL: That's the problem with charity.
You must mean it.

562
00:33:00,960 --> 00:33:02,678
You have to mean things to help people.

563
00:33:02,760 --> 00:33:06,355
Like the time I volunteered
to help out at a soup kitchen...

564
00:33:06,440 --> 00:33:08,670
...and very nearly made it.

565
00:33:08,760 --> 00:33:10,716
Or the time at Amnesty International.

566
00:33:10,800 --> 00:33:14,509
Did you know in Burma you get seven years
in prison for telling jokes?

567
00:33:14,600 --> 00:33:17,990
Next time you laugh, think of Pa Pa Lay,
the Burmese standup comedian.

568
00:33:18,080 --> 00:33:20,992
We're at a crucial stage
in our struggle for human rights...

569
00:33:21,080 --> 00:33:23,799
...which have been grossly abused
by the ruling junta.

570
00:33:23,880 --> 00:33:25,393
We need your support more than ever.

571
00:33:25,480 --> 00:33:27,311
Together we can make a difference....

572
00:33:27,400 --> 00:33:30,551
You're kidding.
And what's your boyfriend say about that?

573
00:33:30,880 --> 00:33:33,997
Wait a minute.
You say you haven't got a boyfriend?

574
00:33:34,080 --> 00:33:36,548
Talk about human rights violations.

575
00:33:41,560 --> 00:33:44,028
Is that right? You're in the bath now?

576
00:33:45,280 --> 00:33:47,350
WlLL: You have to mean things to help people.

577
00:33:47,440 --> 00:33:49,112
Fiona meant Killing Me Softly.

578
00:33:49,200 --> 00:33:53,591
Killing Me Softly meant something to her
and look where she ended up.

579
00:33:55,480 --> 00:33:59,393
Me, I didn't mean anything, about anything,
to anyone.

580
00:33:59,680 --> 00:34:03,229
I knew that guaranteed me
a long, depression-free life.

581
00:34:04,520 --> 00:34:06,715
[Stealth instrumental music]

582
00:34:31,320 --> 00:34:34,596
WILL: Yet over the next few days,
I did have a strange feeling.

583
00:34:34,680 --> 00:34:37,194
Like a presence lurking at the back of my mind.

584
00:34:37,280 --> 00:34:38,952
And I didn't like it.

585
00:34:49,040 --> 00:34:50,632
[Doorbell rings]

586
00:34:51,920 --> 00:34:54,115
You don't have a kid, do you?

587
00:34:55,400 --> 00:34:56,230
What?

588
00:34:56,320 --> 00:34:58,515
You don't have a kid, do you?

589
00:34:58,600 --> 00:35:00,556
Of course I do! What are you on about?

590
00:35:00,640 --> 00:35:01,675
No, you don't.

591
00:35:01,760 --> 00:35:04,911
I've been watching you,
and you don't have a kid.

592
00:35:06,320 --> 00:35:09,153
WlLL: What is it to you, anyway?
MARCUS: Nothing.

593
00:35:09,400 --> 00:35:13,393
Except you've been lying to me,
my mum and my mum's friend.

594
00:35:14,040 --> 00:35:15,553
-Can I come in?
-No.

595
00:35:15,640 --> 00:35:16,709
Why?

596
00:35:16,800 --> 00:35:17,755
'Cause I'm busy.

597
00:35:17,960 --> 00:35:21,919
-What are you doing?
-I'm watching TV.

598
00:35:22,800 --> 00:35:25,109
I could watch it with you, if you like.

599
00:35:25,240 --> 00:35:26,514
That's very nice of you...

600
00:35:26,600 --> 00:35:28,750
...but I usually manage on my own, thanks.

601
00:35:31,560 --> 00:35:33,790
Don't you have homework to do, or something?

602
00:35:33,880 --> 00:35:35,757
-Want to help?
-No, that's not what I meant.

603
00:35:35,840 --> 00:35:37,910
I meant, why don't you go home
and do your homework?

604
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:39,479
I'll do you a deal.

605
00:35:39,560 --> 00:35:43,678
I won't tell anyone you don't have a kid
if you go out with my mum.

606
00:35:47,720 --> 00:35:50,075
You'd want your mum
to go out with someone like me?

607
00:35:50,160 --> 00:35:51,559
MARCUS: You're not too bad.

608
00:35:51,640 --> 00:35:54,712
I mean, you told lies,
but apart from that you seem okay.

609
00:35:55,520 --> 00:35:58,114
And she's sad. I think she'd like a boyfriend.

610
00:35:59,400 --> 00:36:01,311
I can't just go out with someone...

611
00:36:01,400 --> 00:36:04,710
...because you want me to.
I'd have to like the person, as well.

612
00:36:04,800 --> 00:36:08,270
-What's wrong with her?
-Nothing's wrong with her, it's just the system.

613
00:36:08,360 --> 00:36:11,113
That's how it....
I'm not talking about this with you.

614
00:36:11,200 --> 00:36:12,428
Just go.

615
00:36:12,520 --> 00:36:14,351
Okay. But I'll be back.

616
00:36:14,440 --> 00:36:16,351
I'm really scared!

617
00:36:17,920 --> 00:36:21,515
WlLL: That's the best I could come up with,
"I'm scared."

618
00:36:21,760 --> 00:36:24,718
But as a matter of fact, I was.

619
00:36:24,800 --> 00:36:28,395
[Light tapping,
followed by heavy guitar music]

620
00:37:28,280 --> 00:37:29,713
Okay, that's it. Tim, goodbye.

621
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:32,116
-Jill, goodbye. Carol, goodbye.
-Goodbye.

622
00:37:32,200 --> 00:37:35,909
And from me, arrivederci. Bye-bye.

623
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:37,592
[Applause]

624
00:37:44,400 --> 00:37:46,197
Thanks. See you.

625
00:38:01,240 --> 00:38:04,073
HOST: Hello, everybody.
Welcome to the game of Countdown.

626
00:38:04,160 --> 00:38:07,152
You remember yesterday, Carol,
I revealed to a grateful nation...

627
00:38:07,240 --> 00:38:08,992
...that our guest, Tom O'Connell--

628
00:38:09,080 --> 00:38:11,913
CAROL: Yes.
HOST: He, like all of us, changes for each show.

629
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:13,319
But he is such a--

630
00:38:16,800 --> 00:38:18,313
HOST 1: Is that right?
HOST 2: Yeah.

631
00:38:18,400 --> 00:38:21,472
Another term for Hosta, I think.

632
00:38:21,760 --> 00:38:22,715
HOST 1: Yes, well.

633
00:38:22,800 --> 00:38:26,918
Named after Heinrich Christian Funck,
who also invented disco dancing.

634
00:38:29,760 --> 00:38:32,035
Yes. I've got all his audios.

635
00:38:35,200 --> 00:38:37,395
[Chiming instrumental music]

636
00:39:08,520 --> 00:39:12,274
Mum, did you always know
I was going to be a vegetarian?

637
00:39:12,920 --> 00:39:14,148
Yeah, of course I did.

638
00:39:14,240 --> 00:39:17,676
I didn't decide on the spur of the moment
'cause we ran out of sausages.

639
00:39:17,760 --> 00:39:20,035
Did you ask me if I wanted to be a vegetarian?

640
00:39:20,120 --> 00:39:21,917
What, when you were born?

641
00:39:22,080 --> 00:39:24,230
I do the cooking and I don't want to cook meat.

642
00:39:24,320 --> 00:39:26,709
You have to eat what I eat.

643
00:39:27,920 --> 00:39:30,480
But you don't let me go to McDonald's, either.

644
00:39:30,960 --> 00:39:33,474
Is this premature teenage rebellion?

645
00:39:34,080 --> 00:39:36,275
I can't stop you from going to McDonald's.

646
00:39:36,360 --> 00:39:38,874
I'd just be disappointed if you did.

647
00:39:41,680 --> 00:39:44,831
MARCUS: Don't worry, Mum.
I won't go to McDonald's.

648
00:39:45,520 --> 00:39:47,112
[Savage yelling]

649
00:39:48,360 --> 00:39:52,592
MARCUS: After a few visits, Will seemed to think
he had to ask me serious questions.

650
00:39:52,680 --> 00:39:56,593
But I knew he really wanted to watch
Xena: Warrior Princess.

651
00:39:56,680 --> 00:39:58,477
So, how's it going at home then?

652
00:39:58,560 --> 00:40:01,154
-You mean my mum?
-Yeah.

653
00:40:01,560 --> 00:40:03,516
She's all right, thanks.

654
00:40:06,600 --> 00:40:08,955
I mean, you know, she's....

655
00:40:10,560 --> 00:40:14,155
Yeah, I know. No, nothing like that.

656
00:40:17,840 --> 00:40:19,876
Does it still bother you, then?

657
00:40:20,920 --> 00:40:22,319
Does it bother me?

658
00:40:22,400 --> 00:40:23,799
[Boom]

659
00:40:24,120 --> 00:40:25,633
SUZlE: [Distorted] Are you decent?

660
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:31,638
MARCUS: Every single day.

661
00:40:31,840 --> 00:40:34,229
That's why I come here, instead of going home.

662
00:40:34,320 --> 00:40:36,880
A bit. When I think about it.

663
00:40:39,320 --> 00:40:40,992
Fucking hell.

664
00:40:41,680 --> 00:40:44,069
[Light, cheerful instrumental music]

665
00:40:44,160 --> 00:40:47,869
MARCUS: I don't know why he swore like that,
but it made me feel better.

666
00:40:48,760 --> 00:40:52,150
It made me feel like I wasn't being pathetic
to get so scared.

667
00:40:55,520 --> 00:40:58,353
WlLL: I wouldn't make the mistake of asking
about Fiona again.

668
00:40:58,440 --> 00:41:00,158
Marcus was clearly screwed up about it...

669
00:41:00,240 --> 00:41:04,028
...and unfortunately I couldn't think
of anything to say that'd be of any value.

670
00:41:04,120 --> 00:41:06,588
Next time he could talk to Suzie,
or a counselor...

671
00:41:06,680 --> 00:41:09,672
...or anybody capable
of something more than an obscenity.

672
00:41:09,760 --> 00:41:11,876
Shit! It can't be.

673
00:41:11,960 --> 00:41:14,952
[Santa's Super Sleigh is heard
on the store intercom]

674
00:41:15,040 --> 00:41:17,076
WlLL: November-the-sodding-19.

675
00:41:17,160 --> 00:41:21,153
Six weeks before Christmas
and already they were playing the bloody thing.

676
00:41:21,800 --> 00:41:22,915
Dad?

677
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:24,592
[Mystical music]

678
00:41:30,400 --> 00:41:32,311
MARCUS: What was your dad like?

679
00:41:33,080 --> 00:41:34,513
WlLL: A bit sad, really.

680
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:38,470
You know, he wrote one crap song
that turned out to be a massive hit...

681
00:41:38,560 --> 00:41:42,189
...and then spent the rest of his life
trying to write a better one.

682
00:41:42,280 --> 00:41:44,157
Do you ever want to write songs like him?

683
00:41:44,240 --> 00:41:46,356
Is that what the guitar's for?

684
00:41:47,800 --> 00:41:48,835
No.

685
00:41:50,160 --> 00:41:52,549
So, that's just there to look cool.

686
00:41:53,200 --> 00:41:54,076
Yeah.

687
00:41:57,600 --> 00:41:59,830
I like Santa's Super Sleigh.

688
00:41:59,920 --> 00:42:02,514
[Marcus hums Santa's Super Sleigh]

689
00:42:12,200 --> 00:42:14,191
[Marcus stops humming]

690
00:42:16,160 --> 00:42:19,118
KlD 1: Madonna! Come here!
KlD 2: We've got something.

691
00:42:19,400 --> 00:42:21,709
KlD 1: He's getting away, look!
KlD 2: Hurry up!

692
00:42:21,800 --> 00:42:25,236
NARRATOR: On Pet Rescue today,
the clever stoat keeps everyone...

693
00:42:25,320 --> 00:42:27,515
...on their toes in Somerset.

694
00:42:27,600 --> 00:42:30,194
[Soft, feel-good instrumental music]

695
00:42:42,600 --> 00:42:44,795
[Doorbell rings frantically]

696
00:42:47,200 --> 00:42:49,191
[Kid's voices]

697
00:42:52,240 --> 00:42:53,559
Hey!

698
00:42:53,760 --> 00:42:55,637
WlLL: What are you doing?
KlD: Who are you?

699
00:42:55,720 --> 00:42:56,869
WlLL: Who am l?

700
00:42:56,960 --> 00:43:00,999
Bugger off, that's who I am! Go on, piss off!

701
00:43:02,880 --> 00:43:04,393
Who were they, then?

702
00:43:04,480 --> 00:43:05,674
Who?

703
00:43:05,760 --> 00:43:06,795
What do you mean, "Who?"

704
00:43:06,880 --> 00:43:09,633
The ones
trying to embed sweets into your skull.

705
00:43:09,720 --> 00:43:10,755
Oh, them.

706
00:43:10,840 --> 00:43:14,594
They're just a couple of older kids.
They started following me after school.

707
00:43:14,680 --> 00:43:16,272
Does this happen often?

708
00:43:16,360 --> 00:43:18,954
They never chucked sweets before,
they just thought of that.

709
00:43:19,040 --> 00:43:22,430
I'm not talking about the sweets.
The kids trying to kill you.

710
00:43:22,520 --> 00:43:24,750
Yeah, they give me a hard time.

711
00:43:24,960 --> 00:43:28,316
You know, about my hair,
and my clothes and singing and stuff.

712
00:43:28,440 --> 00:43:29,839
And what? And singing?

713
00:43:31,240 --> 00:43:33,993
Sometimes I sing out loud without noticing.

714
00:43:34,720 --> 00:43:36,233
That's not a brilliant idea, is it?

715
00:43:36,320 --> 00:43:40,199
I said I did it without noticing, didn't l?
It just happens!

716
00:43:40,560 --> 00:43:44,155
I'm not going to do it on purpose, am l?
I'm not stupid, you know.

717
00:43:44,280 --> 00:43:48,273
My advice is to keep out of people's way.
Try to make yourself invisible.

718
00:43:48,360 --> 00:43:49,713
How can I be invisible?

719
00:43:49,800 --> 00:43:51,995
One machine in your kitchen
is an invisible machine?

720
00:43:52,080 --> 00:43:53,718
I don't think so.

721
00:43:55,840 --> 00:43:58,593
I just try not to think of it, that's all.

722
00:43:59,760 --> 00:44:03,070
It happens, and I wish it didn't,
but that's life, isn't it?

723
00:44:05,200 --> 00:44:07,634
There's nothing I can do about it.

724
00:44:07,720 --> 00:44:09,711
[Soft instrumental music]

725
00:44:10,920 --> 00:44:11,955
No.

726
00:44:13,760 --> 00:44:16,752
There is something we can do about it, Marcus.

727
00:44:17,480 --> 00:44:18,959
You're coming with me.

728
00:44:19,040 --> 00:44:22,510
MARCUS: I was worried he was going to take me
to the headmistress' office.

729
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:25,797
But instead he took me shopping.

730
00:44:25,880 --> 00:44:27,074
I don't get it.

731
00:44:27,160 --> 00:44:28,752
We're starting with your feet.

732
00:44:28,840 --> 00:44:32,674
I can't make you invisible,
but I can make you blend in with the crowd.

733
00:44:33,480 --> 00:44:36,790
I don't know how to tie them.
They've got these funny strappy things.

734
00:44:36,880 --> 00:44:38,074
It's called Velcro.

735
00:44:38,160 --> 00:44:40,469
It's a revolutionary new technology.

736
00:44:43,080 --> 00:44:46,072
For Christ's sake. It's not hard.

737
00:44:48,280 --> 00:44:50,191
All right, wait a minute, it is a bit hard.

738
00:44:50,280 --> 00:44:53,113
-Everything all right?
-Yeah, thanks.

739
00:44:54,480 --> 00:44:57,119
Pretty trendy, your old man, isn't he?

740
00:45:00,520 --> 00:45:02,476
There. You think you look cool, don't you?

741
00:45:02,560 --> 00:45:03,675
Don't know.

742
00:45:03,840 --> 00:45:07,549
-Do you think I look cool?
-Yeah, Marcus.

743
00:45:08,560 --> 00:45:11,279
-I think you look cool.
-Yeah.

744
00:45:13,800 --> 00:45:16,917
That's it, you got the walk. That's really cool.

745
00:45:18,400 --> 00:45:21,472
Brilliant. High five. Yeah.

746
00:45:21,880 --> 00:45:24,917
WlLL: I was suddenly hit by an extraordinary
rush of well-being.

747
00:45:25,000 --> 00:45:27,719
So this is what people meant by a natural high.

748
00:45:27,800 --> 00:45:29,950
And it only cost $60.

749
00:45:30,040 --> 00:45:32,918
I had made an unhappy boy temporarily happy.

750
00:45:33,080 --> 00:45:35,150
And there wasn't anything in it for me at all.

751
00:45:35,240 --> 00:45:37,231
I didn't even want to shag his mum.

752
00:45:38,360 --> 00:45:39,759
[Thunder]

753
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:42,399
[Sobs]

754
00:45:48,040 --> 00:45:50,713
Marcus! What happened to your shoes?

755
00:45:50,920 --> 00:45:52,512
They stole them.

756
00:46:02,200 --> 00:46:04,111
Why would anyone want to steal your shoes?

757
00:46:04,200 --> 00:46:06,316
MARCUS: I could see I had to tell the truth.

758
00:46:06,400 --> 00:46:09,312
The problem was,
the truth would lead to a lot more questions.

759
00:46:09,400 --> 00:46:10,913
MARCUS: They were nice ones.

760
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:13,275
They were just ordinary brown lace-ups.

761
00:46:13,360 --> 00:46:16,397
No, they weren't. They were cool new trainers.

762
00:46:16,560 --> 00:46:18,790
Where did you get cool new trainers?

763
00:46:18,880 --> 00:46:20,552
MARCUS: She had loads more questions.

764
00:46:20,640 --> 00:46:22,358
Will bought them for me.

765
00:46:23,920 --> 00:46:24,909
Will?

766
00:46:26,080 --> 00:46:28,594
-The guy who took us to lunch?
-Yeah.

767
00:46:28,920 --> 00:46:30,797
MARCUS: He's sort of become my friend.

768
00:46:31,360 --> 00:46:32,998
He's sort of become your friend?

769
00:46:33,080 --> 00:46:35,469
MARCUS: She kept repeating
the last thing I said.

770
00:46:35,560 --> 00:46:37,152
Except she shouted it.

771
00:46:37,440 --> 00:46:39,635
I go round to his place after school.

772
00:46:39,720 --> 00:46:42,280
You go round to his place after school!

773
00:46:42,360 --> 00:46:45,989
-You see, he doesn't really have a kid.
-He doesn't really have a kid?

774
00:46:46,080 --> 00:46:48,116
Can I play computer games now?

775
00:46:48,320 --> 00:46:49,355
Where does he live?

776
00:46:49,440 --> 00:46:52,159
He's not there at the moment.
He's out to dinner.

777
00:46:54,160 --> 00:46:57,038
WlLL: Christine had asked me to dinner
for a pep talk.

778
00:46:57,120 --> 00:47:00,396
You will end up childless and alone.

779
00:47:00,480 --> 00:47:02,436
Both fingers crossed, yeah.

780
00:47:04,280 --> 00:47:05,713
You must have a lot of courage.

781
00:47:05,800 --> 00:47:07,711
Why is that, Christine?

782
00:47:08,360 --> 00:47:11,670
Most people need something in their lives
to keep them afloat...

783
00:47:11,760 --> 00:47:14,672
...and you have absolutely nothing.

784
00:47:15,400 --> 00:47:17,231
Doesn't that scare you?

785
00:47:17,920 --> 00:47:19,797
Do you know what you want?

786
00:47:21,320 --> 00:47:22,833
Yes, I do. I'll have the steak--

787
00:47:22,920 --> 00:47:26,310
What the hell are these little
after-school tea parties about?

788
00:47:26,800 --> 00:47:28,677
Hi. Sorry? What did you say?

789
00:47:28,760 --> 00:47:32,719
I was just wondering why a single,
childless man would want to hang out...

790
00:47:32,800 --> 00:47:35,189
...with a 12-year-old boy every day?

791
00:47:35,280 --> 00:47:38,192
You didn't tell your mum
that you've been coming round?

792
00:47:38,280 --> 00:47:40,589
-I think I forgot.
-Tell me what?

793
00:47:41,240 --> 00:47:42,992
What are you doing with my son?

794
00:47:43,080 --> 00:47:45,310
Wait a minute. What are you suggesting here?

795
00:47:45,400 --> 00:47:47,550
-I'm not suggesting anything.
-I think you are.

796
00:47:47,640 --> 00:47:51,076
You were suggesting that
I've been interfering with your son.

797
00:47:51,160 --> 00:47:55,438
I'm simply asking you
why you entertain 12-year-olds in your flat.

798
00:47:55,520 --> 00:47:57,909
-My God!
-Oh, my God!

799
00:47:58,800 --> 00:48:01,678
What do you have to say for yourself?

800
00:48:02,280 --> 00:48:03,395
Well?

801
00:48:03,480 --> 00:48:05,152
Don't "well" me!

802
00:48:05,240 --> 00:48:06,798
Don't "well" me about this!

803
00:48:06,880 --> 00:48:09,474
He comes over uninvited every night!
Do you know why?

804
00:48:09,560 --> 00:48:13,235
He's having the shit bullied out of him at school!
And you haven't got a clue.

805
00:48:13,320 --> 00:48:15,276
You send him out like a lamb to the slaughter!

806
00:48:15,360 --> 00:48:18,830
He's been taken to pieces every day of the week,
you daft, fucking hippie!

807
00:48:18,920 --> 00:48:21,514
I think you're being a bit melodramatic.
Marcus is fine.

808
00:48:21,600 --> 00:48:25,559
MARCUS: Strange. Will had it right, Mum didn't.
It should be the other way around.

809
00:48:25,640 --> 00:48:27,471
You haven't had much contact with kids.

810
00:48:27,560 --> 00:48:30,199
I used to be a bloody kid!
I went to a bloody school.

811
00:48:30,280 --> 00:48:33,590
I know when kids can't settle down
and when kids are miserable!

812
00:48:33,680 --> 00:48:37,150
Look at him, for Christ's sake!
Don't accuse me of being melodramatic.

813
00:48:37,240 --> 00:48:40,630
-This coming from a woman who tried to--
-Cowabunga!

814
00:48:41,760 --> 00:48:44,354
-What's the matter with you?
-Nothing.

815
00:48:44,520 --> 00:48:46,078
I just felt like a shout.

816
00:48:46,160 --> 00:48:47,388
Jesus, what a family.

817
00:48:47,480 --> 00:48:50,836
Will, you're disturbing the other customers.

818
00:48:50,920 --> 00:48:52,433
It's fine. I'm sorry. I'm done.

819
00:48:52,520 --> 00:48:54,988
-Okay, so, you're not....
-What?

820
00:48:55,840 --> 00:48:57,876
No, I'm not! No, I'm not.

821
00:48:58,520 --> 00:49:00,112
Listen, don't worry about it.

822
00:49:00,200 --> 00:49:02,316
I won't open the door to Marcus again, okay?

823
00:49:02,400 --> 00:49:04,675
I'll be glad to be rid of the pair of you, frankly.

824
00:49:04,760 --> 00:49:06,432
Go on. Bugger off.

825
00:49:08,840 --> 00:49:09,909
Sorry.

826
00:49:18,840 --> 00:49:20,273
So that's it, is it?

827
00:49:20,360 --> 00:49:23,033
You're just out of his life, like that.

828
00:49:23,200 --> 00:49:23,996
Excuse me?

829
00:49:24,080 --> 00:49:26,230
Let's say you're right and I'm wrong.

830
00:49:26,320 --> 00:49:28,151
Let's say there's this whole world...

831
00:49:28,240 --> 00:49:31,596
...that I don't understand,
and somehow, miraculously, you do.

832
00:49:31,680 --> 00:49:33,716
What are you going to do about it?

833
00:49:33,800 --> 00:49:36,633
I'm not going to do anything.
He's none of my business.

834
00:49:36,720 --> 00:49:39,314
-You're a selfish bastard.
-That's what I tell him.

835
00:49:39,400 --> 00:49:42,870
-He always puts himself first.
-But I'm on my own.

836
00:49:43,240 --> 00:49:44,195
It's just me.

837
00:49:44,280 --> 00:49:46,919
I'm not putting myself first.
There's nobody else.

838
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:47,989
Yes, there is!

839
00:49:48,080 --> 00:49:50,389
There's Marcus. You're involved now.

840
00:49:50,480 --> 00:49:52,596
He keeps coming around your bloody house.

841
00:49:52,680 --> 00:49:55,035
You've come into his life for a reason.

842
00:49:55,120 --> 00:49:56,678
You can't just shut him out.

843
00:49:56,760 --> 00:49:59,718
You can't shut life out. "No man is an island."

844
00:49:59,800 --> 00:50:01,677
-She's right, you know.
-Yeah, she is.

845
00:50:01,760 --> 00:50:03,239
No, she's not! She's wrong!

846
00:50:03,320 --> 00:50:05,151
Some men are islands. I'm a bloody island!

847
00:50:05,240 --> 00:50:06,593
I'm bloody lbiza!

848
00:50:07,960 --> 00:50:09,916
What are you talking about?

849
00:50:10,640 --> 00:50:12,949
Do you want to come over for Christmas?

850
00:50:13,040 --> 00:50:15,190
[Soft, peppy instrumental music]

851
00:50:15,440 --> 00:50:18,591
WlLL: No, Marcus, I do not want
to come over for bloody Christmas.

852
00:50:18,800 --> 00:50:22,839
I do not want to spend Christmas
with Miss Granola Suicide and her spawn.

853
00:50:24,440 --> 00:50:26,590
I'd always thought
what you did with Christmas...

854
00:50:26,680 --> 00:50:29,877
...was sort of a statement about
where you stood in life.

855
00:50:30,400 --> 00:50:33,597
I was going to spend this Christmas
the way I usually did.

856
00:50:33,840 --> 00:50:36,798
Watching videos and getting drunk and stoned.

857
00:50:38,840 --> 00:50:41,832
[Santa's Super Sleigh is heard
on the store intercom]

858
00:50:49,080 --> 00:50:52,197
TV CHARACTER: Before you came,
I was all alone.

859
00:50:52,600 --> 00:50:54,431
It is bad to be alone.

860
00:50:54,880 --> 00:50:57,792
Alone, bad.

861
00:50:58,560 --> 00:51:00,437
Friend, good.

862
00:51:00,960 --> 00:51:04,157
Friend, good!

863
00:51:04,240 --> 00:51:05,798
[Characters laugh]

864
00:51:05,880 --> 00:51:07,359
TV CHARACTER: Now come here.

865
00:51:07,800 --> 00:51:10,792
WlLL: The good news was it wasn't
just me and Fiona and Marcus.

866
00:51:10,880 --> 00:51:13,519
The bad news was, well....

867
00:51:13,720 --> 00:51:17,349
So, you're Marcus' dad.

868
00:51:17,800 --> 00:51:23,113
Yeah, I guess so.
And this is my girlfriend, Lindsey.

869
00:51:26,800 --> 00:51:28,199
And Lindsey's mum.

870
00:51:31,280 --> 00:51:32,679
Hi there.

871
00:51:32,760 --> 00:51:34,352
[Feliz Navidad playing]

872
00:51:41,160 --> 00:51:43,913
-Thanks, Dad.
-That's okay.

873
00:51:44,360 --> 00:51:45,952
WlLL: I had to hand it to the kid.

874
00:51:46,040 --> 00:51:49,316
He could be enthusiastic
about some truly crap present.

875
00:51:49,800 --> 00:51:52,234
Wow, a tambourine! Thanks, Mum.

876
00:51:53,000 --> 00:51:54,228
Isn't that cool, Will?

877
00:51:54,320 --> 00:51:56,834
Yeah, that'll come in handy.

878
00:51:56,920 --> 00:51:58,956
I saw it and I thought, "This'll be perfect."

879
00:51:59,040 --> 00:52:03,750
Maybe you can perform at that school concert.
Get a pop group together. Make some friends.

880
00:52:04,280 --> 00:52:05,633
Maybe, Mum.

881
00:52:07,600 --> 00:52:11,388
When you sing,
it brings sunshine and happiness into my heart.

882
00:52:12,480 --> 00:52:13,879
Thanks, Mum.

883
00:52:18,640 --> 00:52:21,200
This one's from me.

884
00:52:28,520 --> 00:52:31,273
Brilliant! What is it?

885
00:52:31,560 --> 00:52:32,959
It's a CD, Marcus.

886
00:52:33,400 --> 00:52:36,039
By Mystikal. They're cool. You'll like them.

887
00:52:36,120 --> 00:52:38,315
And what kind of music is Mystikal?

888
00:52:38,600 --> 00:52:41,398
It's sort of world music.

889
00:52:42,080 --> 00:52:43,593
"Shake Ya Ass."

890
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:45,718
Slash rap type thing.

891
00:52:46,600 --> 00:52:48,397
Shake Ya Ass?

892
00:52:48,480 --> 00:52:49,754
Is he Moroccan?

893
00:52:49,840 --> 00:52:51,717
I'm afraid we haven't got a CD player.

894
00:52:51,800 --> 00:52:52,755
It's great anyway.

895
00:52:52,840 --> 00:52:57,118
I know you haven't got a CD player,
so, I got you one of them as well.

896
00:52:57,400 --> 00:52:59,277
LlNDSEY'S MOM: What a lucky boy.

897
00:53:00,480 --> 00:53:01,799
Look, Mum.

898
00:53:02,280 --> 00:53:04,840
-Open yours, Will.
-All right. Thanks a lot.

899
00:53:09,640 --> 00:53:12,313
-Marcus, is this a joke?
-Yeah.

900
00:53:13,920 --> 00:53:15,114
It's not bad.

901
00:53:15,520 --> 00:53:18,353
SUZlE: Hi. Sorry, I'm dead late!

902
00:53:18,600 --> 00:53:20,511
-Have I missed anything?
-No, come on in.

903
00:53:20,600 --> 00:53:23,068
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas!

904
00:53:23,800 --> 00:53:25,199
WlLL: Hey!

905
00:53:26,520 --> 00:53:28,158
Long time no see.

906
00:53:29,680 --> 00:53:30,829
Where's Megan?

907
00:53:30,920 --> 00:53:35,152
At her dad's. Where's Ned?
At his mum's for Christmas?

908
00:53:37,040 --> 00:53:39,031
[Dog barks in background]

909
00:53:41,960 --> 00:53:42,949
Yeah.

910
00:53:43,080 --> 00:53:46,197
No. I should probably go, shouldn't l?

911
00:53:46,600 --> 00:53:50,275
You could go pose as Santa,
try and shag some carol singers.

912
00:53:50,360 --> 00:53:52,237
Are you a professional Santa?

913
00:53:52,320 --> 00:53:53,514
How lovely!

914
00:53:53,600 --> 00:53:55,989
Right. That's it. I'm off.

915
00:53:56,080 --> 00:53:57,752
Thank you very much. It was great.

916
00:53:57,840 --> 00:54:00,400
Suzie has every right to express her anger.

917
00:54:00,520 --> 00:54:02,033
Yes, and she's expressed it.

918
00:54:02,120 --> 00:54:04,315
Now I have a right to bugger off.

919
00:54:04,400 --> 00:54:06,391
Thanks a lot. 'Bye.

920
00:54:06,480 --> 00:54:07,595
Wait!

921
00:54:08,120 --> 00:54:09,838
He's my friend. I invited him.

922
00:54:09,920 --> 00:54:11,831
I should be able to tell him when to go home.

923
00:54:11,920 --> 00:54:14,195
I haven't told Will to go, Marcus.

924
00:54:14,280 --> 00:54:17,397
Suzie's angry and has every right to be,
and she's telling him so.

925
00:54:17,480 --> 00:54:18,549
She's right, Marcus.

926
00:54:18,640 --> 00:54:20,392
Just leave it, okay?

927
00:54:21,040 --> 00:54:23,315
All he did was make up a kid for a couple weeks.

928
00:54:23,400 --> 00:54:25,834
God, that's nothing. So what? Who cares?

929
00:54:25,920 --> 00:54:27,876
Kids at school do worse than that every day!

930
00:54:27,960 --> 00:54:30,758
The point is, Marcus,
Will left school a long time ago.

931
00:54:30,840 --> 00:54:32,990
He should've grown out
of making people up by now.

932
00:54:33,080 --> 00:54:35,310
-That's for sure.
-It's not fair to gang up on him.

933
00:54:35,400 --> 00:54:37,072
He's been better behaved since then.

934
00:54:37,160 --> 00:54:42,234
He bought me trainers, he lets me go round
to his house and he knows what kids need.

935
00:54:42,320 --> 00:54:45,232
FlONA: What?
Expensive footwear and obscene music?

936
00:54:45,320 --> 00:54:48,278
If there's something you really need
then we can talk about it.

937
00:54:48,360 --> 00:54:51,830
No, we can't. It's not a discussion,
it's an argument, and you always win.

938
00:54:51,920 --> 00:54:54,753
-Why not just tell me what to do?
-I want you to think for yourself!

939
00:54:54,840 --> 00:54:57,274
I'm thinking for myself! And I want Will to stay!

940
00:54:57,360 --> 00:54:59,749
He's not the only one
who ever did anything wrong!

941
00:54:59,840 --> 00:55:01,956
Remember how we met? Remember why?
Because you--

942
00:55:02,040 --> 00:55:06,477
Because you threw a loaf of bread
at a duck's head and killed it, basically.

943
00:55:08,200 --> 00:55:10,191
[Suzie and Fiona laugh]

944
00:55:10,760 --> 00:55:12,955
Excuse me? What's this about a duck?

945
00:55:13,040 --> 00:55:15,395
Are we having duck? Delicious!

946
00:55:16,040 --> 00:55:17,837
[Caroling music]

947
00:55:17,920 --> 00:55:19,876
WlLL: Of course we were not having duck.

948
00:55:19,960 --> 00:55:22,793
Instead we had nut loaf with parsnip gravy.

949
00:55:24,520 --> 00:55:27,193
As I sat there, I had a strange feeling.

950
00:55:27,880 --> 00:55:29,711
I was enjoying myself.

951
00:55:30,400 --> 00:55:32,868
I'd never really enjoyed Christmas before.

952
00:55:33,040 --> 00:55:35,235
My mother used to make me sing
Santa's Super Sleigh...

953
00:55:35,320 --> 00:55:37,675
...in front of my inebriated uncles and aunts...

954
00:55:37,760 --> 00:55:40,069
...just to get at my dad, I think.

955
00:55:40,440 --> 00:55:43,955
But Christmas at Marcus',
I'm ashamed to say it, gave me...

956
00:55:44,040 --> 00:55:45,712
...a warm, fuzzy feeling.

957
00:55:46,160 --> 00:55:49,516
I held that feeling responsible
for the strange events that followed.

958
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:53,150
[Light, pleasant instrumental music]

959
00:55:53,240 --> 00:55:55,834
WlLL: First of all, Marcus got a crush on a girl.

960
00:55:55,920 --> 00:55:57,911
MARCUS: Hello.
ELLlE: Piss off.

961
00:55:59,760 --> 00:56:03,594
WlLL: And then, even stranger, so did I.

962
00:56:04,680 --> 00:56:06,193
It was all Marcus' fault, really...

963
00:56:06,280 --> 00:56:10,398
...because once you open your door
to one person, anyone can come in.

964
00:56:11,120 --> 00:56:13,156
On New Year's Eve, I met Rachel.

965
00:56:13,240 --> 00:56:15,834
She was interesting, smart and attractive.

966
00:56:15,960 --> 00:56:19,396
And for about five minutes,
I had her convinced that I was, too.

967
00:56:19,480 --> 00:56:21,516
...things like political events.

968
00:56:21,600 --> 00:56:22,430
Okay.

969
00:56:22,520 --> 00:56:23,919
You in television?

970
00:56:24,240 --> 00:56:27,437
Am I in television? No.

971
00:56:27,520 --> 00:56:29,636
-Everyone else is in television.
-Yeah.

972
00:56:29,720 --> 00:56:30,835
I watch television.

973
00:56:30,920 --> 00:56:33,878
Right, right.
So you're more in front of it than in it.

974
00:56:33,960 --> 00:56:35,837
-ln it, yeah.
-Yes, I get it, yeah.

975
00:56:35,920 --> 00:56:37,114
WlLL: It was torture.

976
00:56:37,200 --> 00:56:41,432
For five minutes I realized what life would be like
if I were, in any way, interesting.

977
00:56:41,520 --> 00:56:44,910
If I had anything to say for myself,
if I did anything.

978
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:46,672
But I didn't do anything.

979
00:56:47,320 --> 00:56:51,199
And in about 30 seconds she'd know
and she'd be gone like a shot.

980
00:56:51,400 --> 00:56:53,789
So what do you do?

981
00:56:55,920 --> 00:56:59,276
I'm sort of taking a bit of time off at the moment.

982
00:56:59,360 --> 00:57:01,669
